    /*
    the typical format of a SWIFT code:

    8-character SWIFT code (e.g., AAAABBBB):
    The first 4 characters represent the bank code (only letters).
    The next 2 characters represent the country code (only letters).
    The last 2 characters represent the location code (letters and digits).
    
    11-character SWIFT code (e.g., AAAABBBBCCC):
    The first 4 characters represent the bank code (only letters).
    The next 2 characters represent the country code (only letters).
    The next 2 characters represent the location code (letters and digits).
    The last 3 characters (optional) represent the branch code (letters and digits).
    Note that the country code follows the ISO 3166-1 alpha-2 standard, which consists of two-letter country codes.
    
    Here are a few examples of valid SWIFT codes:
    
    ABNANL2A: SWIFT code for ABN AMRO Bank in the Netherlands.
    CITIUS33: SWIFT code for Citibank in the United States.
    BARCGB22XXX: SWIFT code for Barclays Bank PLC in the United Kingdom, including the branch code "XXX."
        
    */
